The following assumptions were made regarding the financial plan:
&nbsp;
* Predicted sales increase of 15\%
&nbsp;
* Dividend payout ratio of 40\%
&nbsp;
* Predicted increase in the balance sheet (assets and current liabilities) accounts proportional to sales
&nbsp;
* Tax rate of 25\%

Now, let us compute the increase in the sales:
&nbsp;
$$\begin{aligned}
\text{Increase in Sales}&=\text{Sales}\times\text{Rate of Increase}\\[12pt]
&={\$7,900}\times{15\%}\\[12pt]
&=\boxed{\$1,185}\\
\end{aligned}$$
&nbsp;
**The increase in the sales amounts to \$1,185.**

Now, let us compute the projected sales:
&nbsp;
$$\begin{aligned}
\text{Projected Sales}&=\text{Sales}+\text{Increase in Sales}\\[12pt]
&={\$7,900}+{\$1,185}\\[12pt]
&=\boxed{\$9,085}\\
\end{aligned}$$
&nbsp;
**The projected sales is \$9,085.**

Now, let us compute the percentage of cost in proportion to the sales:
&nbsp;
$$\begin{aligned}
\text{Percentage of Cost}&=\frac{\text{Cost}}{\text{Sales}}\times100\\[12pt]
&=\frac{\$5,500}{\$7,900}\times100\\[12pt]
&={0.70}\times100\\[12pt]
&=\boxed{70\%}\\
\end{aligned}$$
&nbsp;
**The percentage of cost in proportion to the sales is 70\%.**

Now, let us compute the projected cost:
&nbsp;
$$\begin{aligned}
\text{Projected Cost}&=\text{Projected Sales}\times\text{Rate}\\[12pt]
&={\$9,085}\times{70\%}\\[12pt]
&=\boxed{\$6,359.50}\\
\end{aligned}$$
&nbsp;
**The projected cost is \$6,359.50.**

Now, let us compute the projected taxable income:
&nbsp;
$$\begin{aligned}
\text{Projected Taxable Income}&=\text{Projected Sales}-\text{Projected Cost}\\[12pt]
&={\$9,085}-{\$6,359.50}\\[12pt]
&=\boxed{\$2,725.50}\\
\end{aligned}$$
&nbsp;
**The projected Taxable income is \$2,725.50.**

Now, let us compute the taxes:
&nbsp;
$$\begin{aligned}
\text{Taxes}&=\text{Sales}\times\text{Rate}\\[12pt]
&={\$2,725.50}\times{25\%}\\[12pt]
&=\boxed{\$681.38}\\
\end{aligned}$$
&nbsp;
**The projected taxes is \$681.38.**

Now, let us compute the projected net income:
&nbsp;
$$\begin{aligned}
\text{Projected Net Income}&=\text{Taxable Income}-\text{Taxes}\\[12pt]
&={\$2,725.50}-{\$681.38}\\[12pt]
&=\boxed{\$2,044.12}\\
\end{aligned}$$
&nbsp;
**The projected net income is \$2,044.12.**

Now, let us compute the percentage of current assets in proportion to the sales:
&nbsp;
$$\begin{aligned}
\text{Percentage of Current Asset}&=\frac{\text{Asset}}{\text{Sales}}\times100\\[12pt]
&=\frac{\$3,900}{\$7,900}\times100\\[12pt]
&={0.49}\times100\\[12pt]
&=\boxed{49\%}\\
\end{aligned}$$
&nbsp;
**The percentage of current asset in proportion to the sales is 49\%.**

Now, let us compute the projected current assets:
&nbsp;
$$\begin{aligned}
\text{Projected Current Assets}&=\text{Sales}\times\text{Rate}\\[12pt]
&={\$9,085}\times{49\%}\\[12pt]
&=\boxed{\$4,451.65}\\
\end{aligned}$$
&nbsp;
**The projected current assets is \$4,451.65.**

Now, let us compute the percentage of fixed assets in proportion to the sales:
&nbsp;
$$\begin{aligned}
\text{Percentage of Fixed Asset}&=\frac{\text{Asset}}{\text{Sales}}\times100\\[12pt]
&=\frac{\$8,600}{\$7,900}\times100\\[12pt]
&={1.09}\times100\\[12pt]
&=\boxed{109\%}\\
\end{aligned}$$
&nbsp;
**The percentage of fixed asset in proportion to the sales is 109\%.**

Now, let us compute the projected fixed assets:
&nbsp;
$$\begin{aligned}
\text{Projected Fixed Assets}&=\text{Sales}\times\text{Rate}\\[12pt]
&={\$9,085}\times{109\%}\\[12pt]
&=\boxed{\$9,902.65}\\
\end{aligned}$$
&nbsp;
**The projected fixed assets is \$9,902.65.**

Now, let us compute the projected assets:
&nbsp;
$$\begin{aligned}
\text{Projected Assets}&=\text{Current Assets}+\text{Fixed Assets}\\[12pt]
&={\$4,451.65}\times{\$9,902.65}\\[12pt]
&=\boxed{\$14,354.30}\\
\end{aligned}$$
&nbsp;
**The projected assets is \$14,354.30.**

Now, let us compute the percentage of current liabilities in proportion to the sales:
&nbsp;
$$\begin{aligned}
\text{Percentage of Current liabilities}&=\frac{\text{Asset}}{\text{Sales}}\times100\\[12pt]
&=\frac{\$2,100}{\$7,900}\times100\\[12pt]
&={0.27}\times100\\[12pt]
&=\boxed{27\%}\\
\end{aligned}$$
&nbsp;
**The percentage of current liabilities in proportion to the sales is 27\%.**

Now, let us compute the projected current liabilities:
&nbsp;
$$\begin{aligned}
\text{Projected Current liabilities }&=\text{Sales}\times\text{Rate}\\[12pt]
&={\$9,085}\times{27\%}\\[12pt]
&=\boxed{\$2,452.95}\\
\end{aligned}$$
&nbsp;
**The projected current liabilities is \$2,452.95.**

Now, let us compute the dividend:
&nbsp;
$$\begin{aligned}
\text{Dividend}&=\text{Net Income}\times\text{Rate}\\[12pt]
&={\$1,800}\times{40\%}\\[12pt]
&=\boxed{\$720}\\
\end{aligned}$$
&nbsp;
**The dividend is \$720.**

Now, let us compute the projected dividend:
&nbsp;
$$\begin{aligned}
\text{Projected Dividend}&=\text{Net Income}\times\text{Rate}\\[12pt]
&={\$2,044.12}\times{40\%}\\[12pt]
&=\boxed{\$974.73}\\
\end{aligned}$$
&nbsp;
**The projected dividend is \$974.73.**

Now, let us compute the total equity:
&nbsp;
$$\begin{aligned}
\text{Total Equity}&=\text{Equity}+\text{Dividend}\\[12pt]
&={\$6,700}+{\$974.73}\\[12pt]
&=\boxed{\$7,674.73}\\
\end{aligned}$$
&nbsp;
**The total equity amounts to \$7,674.73.**

Now, let us compute the total debt and equity:
&nbsp;
$$\begin{aligned}
\text{Total}&=\text{Current Liabilities}+\text{Long-Term Debt}+\text{Equity}\\[12pt]
&={\$2,452.95}+{\$3,700}+{\$7,674.73}\\[12pt]
&=\boxed{\$13,827.68}\\
\end{aligned}$$
&nbsp;
**The total debt and equity amounts to \$13,827.68.**

To balance the total debt and equity and the total assets, we are to compute the external financing needed by the company:
&nbsp;
$$\begin{aligned}
\text{EFN}&=\text{Total Assets}-\text{Total Debt and Equity}\\[12pt]
&={\$14,354.30}-{\$13,827.68}\\[12pt]
&=\boxed{\$526.62}\\
\end{aligned}$$
&nbsp;
**The external financing needed amounts to \$526.62.**

### Next, let us provide the given balance sheet.

$$
\begin{array}{c}
\textbf{Assouad, Inc.}\\
\text{Balance Sheet}
\end{array}
$$

$$
\begin{array}{lrlr}
\textbf{Description}&\underline{\textbf{Amount}}&\textbf{Description}&\underline{\textbf{Amount}}\\[10pt]
\text{Current Assets}&\$3,900.00&\text{Current Liabilities}&\$2,100.00\\
\text{Fixed Assets}&\text{8,600.00}&\text{Long-term debt}&3,700.00\\
&\underline{\text{-----------}}&\text{Equity}&\underline{6,700.00}\\
\textbf{Total}&\underline{\underline{\$12,500.00}}&\textbf{Total}&\underline{\underline{\$12,500.00}}
\end{array}
$$

### Last, provide the income statement.
$$
\begin{array}{c}
\textbf{Assouad, Inc.}\\
\text{Income Statement}
\end{array}
$$

$$
\begin{array}{lr}
\textbf{Description}&\underline{\textbf{Amount}}\\[10pt]
\text{Sales}&\$7,900.00\\
\text{Cost of Sales}&\underline{5,500.00}\\
\text{Taxable Income}&2,400.00\\
\text{Taxes(25\%)}&\underline{600.00}\\
\textbf{Net Income}&\underline{\underline{\$1,800.00}}

\end{array}
$$

### Compute the projected sales.

The sales are expected to increase by exactly 15%, or the total increase will be 115%. We multiply the percentage increase with the current sales to compute the expected sales.

$$
\begin{aligned}
\textbf{Projected Sales}&= \text{Current Sales} \times \text{Projected Increase in Sales}\\[15pt]
&= \$7,900.00 \times 115\%\\[15pt]
&= \boxed{\textbf{\$9,085.00}}

\end{aligned}
$$

Therefore, the total projected sales are set at **$9,085.00**.

Therefore, the percentage of the cost of sales from sales is as follows.

$$
\begin{aligned}
\textbf{Percentage of Cost of Sales from Sales}&= \dfrac{\$5,500.00}{\$7,900.00}\\[15pt]
&= 0.6962 \times 100\\[15pt]

&= \boxed{\textbf{69.62\%}}


\end{aligned}
$$

The percentage of the cost of sales from the sales is **69.62%**.

Therefore, the project cost of sales is as follows.

$$
\begin{aligned}
\textbf{Projected Cost of Sales}&= \$9,085.00 \times 69.62\%\\[15pt]
&=\boxed{\textbf{\$6,324.98}}

\end{aligned}
$$

The projected cost of sales is **$6,324.98**.

### Compute the business tax.

The business tax is treated as operating cost, which is deducted from the taxable income to compute the net income.

$$
\begin{aligned}
\textbf{Business Tax}&= \$2,760.02 \times 25\%\\[15pt]
&=\boxed{\textbf{\$690.00}}

\end{aligned}
$$

Therefore, the business tax is **$690.00**.

### Compute the projected current assets based on the percentage of increase in sales.

Current assets are to be projected in proportion to the increase in sales.


$$
\begin{aligned}
\textbf{Projected Current Assets}&= \text{Current Assets} \times \text{Percentage of increase in sales}\\[15pt]
&= \$3,900.00  \times 115\%\\[15pt]
&= \boxed{\textbf{\$4,485.00}} 
\end{aligned}
$$

Therefore, the projected current assets are **$4,485.00**.

### Compute the projected fixed assets based on the percentage of increase in sales.

Fixed assets are to be projected in proportion to the increase in sales.


$$
\begin{aligned}
\textbf{Projected Fixed Assets}&= \text{Fixed Assets} \times \text{Percentage of increase in sales}\\[15pt]
&= \$8,600.00  \times 115\%\\[15pt]
&= \boxed{\textbf{\$9,890.00}} 
\end{aligned}
$$

Therefore, the projected fixed assets are **$9,890.00**.

### Compute the projected current liabilities based on the percentage of increase in sales.

Liabilities are to be projected in proportion to the increase in sales.


$$
\begin{aligned}
\textbf{Projected Current Liabilities}&= \text{Current Liabilities} \times \text{Percentage of increase in sales}\\[15pt]
&= \$2,100.00  \times 115\%\\[15pt]
&= \boxed{\textbf{\$2,415.00}} 
\end{aligned}
$$

Therefore, the projected current liabilities are **$2,415.00**.

### Prepare the Pro Forma balance sheet.

$$
\begin{array}{c}
\textbf{Assouad, Inc.}\\
\text{Pro Forma}\\

\text{Balance Sheet}
\end{array}
$$

$$
\begin{array}{lrlr}
\textbf{Description}&\underline{\textbf{Amount}}&\textbf{Description}&\underline{\textbf{Amount}}\\[10pt]
\text{Current Assets}&\$4,485.00&\text{Current Liabilities}&\$2,415.00\\
\text{Fixed Assets}&\text{9,890.00}&\text{Long-term debt}&3,700.00\\
&\underline{\text{-----------}}&\text{Equity}&\underline{7,942.01}\\
\textbf{Total}&\underline{\underline{\$14,375.00}}&\textbf{Total}&\underline{\underline{\$14,057.01}}\\[10pt]
&&\textbf{EFN}&\underline{\$317.99}\\
&&\textbf{Total}&\underline{\underline{\$14,375.00}}
\end{array}
$$

Therefore, the total balance of the balance sheet is **$14,375.00**.
